===Etymology===
From [[w:Latin|Latin]] ''[[divide et impera]]''


It is thought that Philip II of Macedon (father of Alexander the Great) said this in reference to the rulers of the Greek city states. What he meant was that it was smartest to play enemies against each other and make them weaker, thus making them much easier to take over and rule. After takeover, it was vital to destroy and prevent communication between rebellious groups as soon as possible, in order to prevent them from organizing. Cool beans, this Philip was.

